Differences in composition and appearanc: The expert notes that in the photograph of President Trump in the Situation Room, everyone is dressed neatly in suit and tie, looking into the camera, and appears emotionally composed. By contrast, in the photograph of President Obama, some individuals are lacking suit coats and/or ties, no one is looking at the camera, and there is a palpable tension in the room.
Presence of colorful ethernet cables: The expert points out that the table in the photograph of President Trump contains a bunch of colorful ethernet cables that don't appear to be connected to anything. This detail raises questions about the authenticity of the photograph.
Timestamp analysis: Pete Souza, the official White House photographer who took the photograph of President Obama in the Situation Room during the raid that killed Osama bin Laden, suggested that the timestamp of the photograph of President Trump indicates it was taken well after the raid that led to the death of Abu Bakr al-Baghdadi. This raises doubts about the timing and authenticity of the photograph.
Golf outing records and reports: Online commenters highlighted records and reports suggesting that President Trump was on a golf outing until just after 3 p.m. on the day of the raid and didn't arrive at the White House until 4:18 p.m., which is past the reported time the raid was taking place. This discrepancy further fuels skepticism about the authenticity of the claim.
